   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,166:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The net effect:
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,174:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  when a Fragile-wrapped VLA misbehaves, you don
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,180:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: '
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,361:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: t stare at a loss curve wondering what went
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,485:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: wrong. You open the dashboard, see which (chart, code) state the system was in, inspect the force decomposition
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,522:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: acting on it, check whether energy was conserved, and read the diagnostic that fired. Every internal quantity has a
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,532:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: name, a geometric meaning, and a visual representation.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,547:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5. Reward from Geometry: Inverse Optimal Control Without Reward Labels
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,557:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.1 The Problem: VLAs Have No Reward Signal
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,567:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: A VLA takes images and a language instruction and outputs 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,576:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: actions
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,683:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: . That is all. There is no reward signal, no value
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,731:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: head, no critic network. The model is a black-box policy: observation in, action out. If you want to do planning,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,741:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: rollout evaluation, safety filtering, or any form of reasoning about 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,747:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,755:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: is this trajectory good?
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,761:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,769:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: , you have nothing to
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,776:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: work with.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,786:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: This is a fundamental limitation for deployment. Without a reward model you cannot:
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,793:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,802:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Filter unsafe trajectories
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,810:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  before execution (you have no criterion for 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,817:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,823:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: safe
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,830:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: "
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,836:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: )
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,843:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,850:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Plan ahead
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,860:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  by evaluating candidate action sequences (you have no objective to maximize)
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,867:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,872:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Detect degradation
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,882:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  when the policy starts producing subtly worse trajectories (you have no quality
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,888:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: metric)
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,891:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,896:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Transfer to new tasks
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,901:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  by reward shaping (you have no reward to shape)
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,980:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Standard approaches require either explicit reward engineering (task-specific, brittle) or training a separate reward
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:54,998:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: model from human preference data (RLHF-style, expensive). Both require supervision that the raw VLA
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,003:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: demonstrations do not provide.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,009:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: 5.2 The Geometric Shell Learns a Reward Model for Free
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,098:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The Fragile geometric shell solves this. By wrapping a frozen VLA and training on its demonstration trajectories,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,115:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: the shell learns three complementary reward signals -- none of which require explicit reward labels. The key insight
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,144:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: is that 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,153:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: fitting a Hamiltonian system to demonstrations is a form of inverse optimal control
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,189:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: : the potential energy
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,206:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: function that generates the observed trajectories IS the implicit cost function.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,219:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Signal 1: The Effective Potential $
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,226:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,233:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Phi
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,240:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,247:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,254:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,265:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{eff}}$ (Continuous Value Landscape)
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,279:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The world model learns a scalar field on the Poincare ball:
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,286:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: $$
