   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,327:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: alpha
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,330:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: ,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,335:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  U(z) + (1-
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,338:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,342:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: alpha)
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,346:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: ,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,350:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  V
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,354:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,358:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,361:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,366:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{critic}}(z, K) + 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,370:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,374:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: gamma
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,378:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,382:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,386:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,391:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{risk}}
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,395:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: ,
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,399:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,403:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,407:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Psi
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,411:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,415:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,419:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,424:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{risk}}(z, K)$$
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,431:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: where $U(z)$ is an analytic radial drive term, $V
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,435:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,439:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,443:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,450:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{critic}}$ is a learned chart-conditioned value field, and $
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,455:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,459:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Psi
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,464:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,468:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,472:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,588:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{risk}}$ is a learned risk penalty. The world model is trained to reproduce demonstrated trajectories via
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,624:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Hamiltonian integration. By classical results in optimal control (the Pontryagin maximum principle), the potential
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,632:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: that generates optimal trajectories encodes which states the demonstrations prefer.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,636:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: This means: 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,640:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: $R
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,644:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,648:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,651:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,655:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Phi}(z, K) = -
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,659:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,662:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: Phi
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,666:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: _
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,669:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: {
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,673:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: \
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,678:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: text{eff}}(z, K)$ is an implicit reward function.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,804:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  States where
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,917:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: demonstrations spend time have low potential (the integrator naturally flows there). States demonstrations avoid
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,951:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: have high potential (the integrator flows away). No reward label was needed -- the reward is a byproduct of fitting
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,959:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: the dynamics. This is exactly the classical 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,965:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: inverse reinforcement learning
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,978:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment:  result, but derived geometrically rather
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,984:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: than via reward function search.
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,993:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The force decomposition gives additional structure that a scalar reward model cannot:
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:55,999:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: l
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:56,004:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: The 
   DEBUG: 2026-03-04 12:27:56,012:      pdf_renderer.py:  470: printSegment: conservative force
